    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 4, 2026\n\n---\n\n## ✈️ Iran Shoots Down Two More US Warplanes — Day 36 Crosses Another Line\n\nDay 36. Iran claimed to have downed two US fighter jets — one in Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad province, one crashing into the Gulf. Two crew members were rescued; at least one remains missing. Simultaneously, Israel destroyed two bridges over the Litani River in Lebanon.\n\n- **The escalation:** Day 35 was one F-15. Day 36 is two more. Manned aircraft going down is a different category from drone losses, and the trajectory of this conflict has a direction.\n- **The Lebanon angle:** Israel is opening a second theater while the US absorbs aerial losses. Wars with multiple simultaneous fronts don't tend to de-escalate on their own timetable.\n\n*Two more downed warplanes. A crew member still missing. Israel bombing Lebanon. The war that was supposed to end \"shortly\" is now 36 days old.*\n\n**Sources:** [Al Jazeera liveblog (April 4)](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/liveblog/2026/4/4/iran-war-live-tehran-downs-2-us-warplanes-israel-bombs-lebanon-bridges) | [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/03/g-s1-116314/iran-hits-gulf-refineries-as-trump-warns-u-s-will-attack-iranian-bridges-power-plants)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 Iran Hit an Abu Dhabi Aluminum Smelter and Sent Metal Prices to a 4-Year High\n\nIran struck the Al-Taweelah aluminum complex in Abu Dhabi — operated by Emirates Global Aluminium, one of the largest producers in the world at 1.6M metric tons of annual capacity. Global aluminum hit **$3,500/metric ton** on the LME, a four-year high.\n\n- **Why it matters:** aluminum goes into cars, planes, electronics, and construction. A four-year price spike on a critical industrial input means every downstream manufacturer is repricing their next quarter. This is not an abstract geopolitics story.\n- **The targeting logic:** the UAE is not party to the US-Iran war. Striking Abu Dhabi's industrial infrastructure is a message: no one in the Gulf is neutral.\n\n*One drone strike on an aluminum smelter and every car manufacturer on earth has to reprice their next quarter. Welcome to 2026.*\n\n**Sources:** [FinancialContent/MarketMinute](https://markets.financialcontent.com/stocks/article/marketminute-2026-4-2-molten-geopolitics-iranian-strikes-on-gulf-smelters-send-aluminum-prices-to-4-year-highs)\n\n---\n\n## 💡 Trump Threatened to Bomb Iran's Water Supply If Hormuz Stays Closed\n\nAs the conflict entered week five, Trump publicly threatened to strike Iranian **power grids and desalination plants** unless Iran reopens the Strait of Hormuz. About 20% of global oil and LNG remains blocked. Iranian casualties now stand at 2,076 killed and 26,500 wounded since February 28.\n\n- **Desalination plants:** Iran gets a significant portion of its fresh water from desalination. Destroying that infrastructure in an arid country is a different category of action than hitting military targets. International law has a precise term for it.\n- **The incentive structure:** Iran's motive to keep the strait closed is not obviously weaker than the US threat to escalate. The blockade costs the global economy far more than it costs Iran.\n\n*Threatening to destroy the water supply of a country of 90 million people. The phrase \"war crimes\" is doing a lot of heavy lifting this week.*\n\n**Sources:** [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/03/g-s1-116314/iran-hits-gulf-refineries-as-trump-warns-u-s-will-attack-iranian-bridges-power-plants) | [Al Jazeera day 35](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/4/3/iran-war-what-is-happening-on-day-35-of-us-israeli-attacks)\n\n---\n\n## 🤝 Xi and Trump Are Apparently About to Cut a Trade Deal (While Everything Else Is On Fire)\n\nDespite a war, $109 oil, and $166B in illegal tariff refunds, US and Chinese officials have signaled momentum toward a Xi-Trump summit in April expected to produce a tentative trade arrangement — the first major US-China diplomatic move since the Supreme Court struck down IEEPA tariffs in February.\n\n- **The framing:** the US is simultaneously at war in the Middle East, managing a massive tariff refund process, and finding time to negotiate with Beijing. Multitasking at scale.\n- **What \"tentative arrangement\" means:** in US-China trade diplomacy, this typically unlocks a 90-day pause on the current threat level. Structural changes take years. Investors are pricing in the pause.\n\n*The Middle East is on fire, oil is at $109, and somehow the big diplomatic news is a possible US-China trade deal. Geopolitics contains multitudes.*\n\n**Sources:** [Convera FX Outlook April 2026](https://convera.com/blog/market-insights/fx-research/monthly-global-fx-outlook/fx-outlook-april-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🌐 The World Built New Trade Routes Around America. They Work Fine.\n\nA Marketplace investigation published April 1: while the US spent a year building tariff walls, the rest of the world spent a year building new trade agreements — without the US. New bilateral and regional deals were signed across Asia, Europe, and South America. Dollar-denominated dependency is down. Non-US supply chains are institutionalized.\n\n- **The one-year ledger:** 89,000 fewer US manufacturing jobs, a record US goods trade deficit in 2025, $600–$1,000+ in extra annual costs per household. The tariffs were meant to fix the trade deficit. They made it worse.\n- **The structural shift:** partners who rerouted around US tariffs didn't just find workarounds — they established permanent commercial relationships. Not easily undone by a future administration.\n\n*The US spent a year building walls. Everyone else spent a year building doors that don't go through the US.*\n\n**Sources:** [Marketplace](https://www.marketplace.org/story/2026/04/01/after-tariffs-global-trade-moves-on-without-us) | [NPR: one year of tariffs](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/02/nx-s1-5766424/trump-tariffs-inflation-economy)\n\n---\n\n## 🖥️ The US Is Considering Requiring Government Approval for Every GPU Shipped Anywhere\n\nUS regulators have drafted rules requiring government approval for AI chip exports to **any country** — not just adversaries. Tiered system: cursory review for under 1,000 GPUs, government certifications required for 200,000+ GPU deployments. Nvidia and AMD would need US approval to ship to allied democracies.\n\n- **The scope creep:** chip controls started with China. Then Russia. Then adversaries broadly. The new draft would cover allies too. Every GPU, anywhere.\n- **The trajectory:** Nvidia and AMD have been lobbying against this for months. The rules remain a draft — but the direction of US semiconductor policy is consistent: more controls, broader scope, faster ratchet.\n\n*Started with China. Then adversaries. Now potentially everyone. The export control escalation ladder has many rungs left.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/05/us-reportedly-considering-sweeping-new-chip-export-controls/) | [Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/03/05/nvidia-and-amd-could-face-worldwide-ai-chip-export/)"
